replies.body:
I agree, sort of.  I feel about traits and tools, how you feel about classes.  Champs with movement, disables, and waveclear etc should be missing something, which usually should be late game damage.  A good balanced reflection of this is {{champion:127}}, a champ that has those traits but cant really carry, and an unbalanced example would be those like {{champion:6}} .  Another good example of a balanced champ with a lot of tools is {{champion:497}} bc he has little damage, while {{champion:266}} has every trait covered while also being able to carry is woefully overloaded and unbalanced.  The champs that pretty much just do just damage and are riskier should be the definitive late game damage champs along with a handful of marksmen.  Right now everyone just carries and it makes little sense and has to be hard to learn.  Carrying in itself is a trait.  Carries are weak early and the strongest late.  

{{champion:107}} {{champion:56}} {{champion:69}} {{champion:131}} {{champion:136}} {{champion:38}} {{champion:23}} {{champion:114}} 

The few risky outplay champs should carry with leads bc the ability to outplay comes from tools in the champs' kit, therefore they come at a cost (late game)

{{champion:157}} {{champion:92}} {{champion:39}} {{champion:7}} 


Tanks are imperative to having a fun game.  But it is important Riot realizes all tanks are macro champs.  And yes tanks should beat carries before they are carrying (forces teamwork).  It should be a definitive part of the game that one learns.   Later game tanks should be about zoning, peeling, and their ults (engages).  Outplay tools on tanks mean they are supports since they have extra ways to survive/disable/engage.
